Defendant Shawn Robert Schroth in court with attorney Stephen Andrew Sargent.  Randy P. Sitzberger appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  As to counts 1 and 3:    Defendant was advised of constitutional rights and maximum penalties, and further advised that if not a United States citizen deportation is possible. Defendant examined as to plea, and entered a plea of guilty.  Court found defendant freely, voluntarily and intelligently waived all constitutional rights. Plea questionnaire waiver of rights and addendum to plea questionnaire received and filed. Parties stipulated to the criminal complaint as factual basis to sustain defendant's plea. Court found defendant guilty as charged in the Information and ordered a Judgment of Conviction be entered into the record.  The Court advised defendant that as a convicted felon not to possess any firearms/body armor.    Court further advised defendant of voting ineligibility.   
Count 2 is ordered dismissed.
As to count 1:    Sentencing proceeded.  Statements made by the state, defense and defendant. 
The Court sentenced the defendant to a TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of 42 MONTHS, CONSECUTIVE to 15CF3652 with credit for  0 days served. The INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 18 MONTHS.  The TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION IS  24 MONTHS.
 The defendant IS eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program and/or the Substance Abuse Program.
CONDITIONS OF SUPERVISION:
*Obtain AODA assessment- complete follow-up treatment;
*Absolute sobriety- random urine screens and breathalyzer tests;
*Pay all supervision fees;
*Provide DNA sample- pay surcharge;
*Pay victim/witness surcharge;  
 The Court ordered defendant to pay a fine of $600.00 plus all mandatory costs, penalties, surcharges, including $50.00 ignition interlock surcharge. Court ordered AODA assessment and Driver's Safety Plan; cooperate with any treatment recommended.  Court ordered defendant's driving privileges revoked for a period of 30 months.  Court ordered defendant restricted to operation of vehicles equipped with an ignition interlock device for 30 months to commence upon eligibility to reinstate license. 
The Court ordered that all financial obligations and and those orderd in count 3 be paid through collection by the Department of Corrections from 25% of funds under Sec. 973.05(4)(b) and as a condition of extended supervision.  Any remaining balance to convert to civil judgment.
As to count 3:    The Court ordered the Defendant to serve 1 year in the House of Correction, concurrent  with count 1 credit for 0 days time served.    The court orders defendant to pay all applicable costs, fees, assessments and surcharges, provide for DNA and surcharge as a condition of extended supervision as imposed in count 1 and failure to do so will result in entry of civil judgment.
Defendant remanded.
